{
  "text": "Research on the impacts of plastics on marine biota has mainly focused on large plastic items which may have direct negative impacts on over 260 species, generally through ingestion and entanglement [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . However, there is increasing concern about the impacts of smaller plastics on marine organisms about which much less is known [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Over time, biological, chemical and physical processes degrade large plastic items into microplastics [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] (< 1 mm in diameter), increasing their availability to marine biota [CITATION_8] . Being similar in size to plankton and suspended organic particles, microplastics can be mistakenly ingested as food and, as such, are inadvertently consumed by a variety of organisms [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] .",
